Sure, I can provide a Java solution that does not use loops or recursion. The idea is to use the fact that if a number is a power of three, its base-3 representation has only one '1' and all other digits are '0'. We can use this fact to check if a number is a power of three by converting it to base-3 and checking if it has only one '1'. However, Java does not support base-3 conversion directly. So, we will use a mathematical approach.

Here is the Java code:

```java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(27)); // true
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(0)); // false
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(-1)); // false
    }

    public static boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n < 1) {
            return false;
        }
        double logBase3 = Math.log10(n) / Math.log10(3);
        return ((logBase3 - Math.floor(logBase3)) == 0);
    }
}
```

In this code, we first check if the number is less than 1 (i.e., it is either 0 or a negative number), in which case we return false. Then, we calculate the logarithm of the number in base-3 using the change of base formula. If the number is a power of three, this logarithm should be an integer. We check this by subtracting the floor of the logarithm from the logarithm itself. If the result is 0, it means that the logarithm is an integer and the number is a power of three.

